mmon was the goal of improving life, at least as they saw it. In every other way, the communities varied greatly, ranging from a cooperative colony in Englewood founded by Upton Sinclair, to an anarchist village in Piscataway centered on an educational experiment, to the fascinating Physical Culture City in Spotswood, where drugs, tobacco, and corsets were banned, but where nudity was widespread. Despite their grand intentions, all but one of the utopias—a single-tax colony in Berkeley Heights—failed to survive. But Buchan shows how each of them left a legacy of much more than the buildings or street names that remain today—legacies that are inspiring, surprising, and often outright quirky.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCommunitiesxHistoryxNew Jersey. 0aCommunitieszNew JerseyxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxHistoryxNew Jersey. 0aImmigrantszNew JerseyxHistory. 0aUtopian socialismxHistoryxNew Jersey. 0aUtopian socialismzNew JerseyxHistory. 7aTravel / General.2bisacsh  aUtopia, New Jersey, Travels in the Nearest Eden, Perdita Buchan, NJ, New Jersey, NJ residents, New Jersey residents, utopian experiments, utopia, philosophical organizations, philanthropical organizations, philosophical individuals, philanthropical individuals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354395640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813543956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813543956/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles